<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-528-404  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 528 404.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Byte  June 1990 v15 n6 p256(5).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Images from the deep: the Woods Hole Jason Project uses a uniquevehicle system and a fiber-optic network to transmit data fromunder the sea.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Mindell, David A.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution (Woods Hole, MA) DeepSubmergence Laboratory (DSL) employs a 10M-bit/sec ProteonProNET-10 fiber-optic local area network (LAN) to link the variouscomputers, sensors, controllers and manipulators in the DSL'sJason deep-ocean remotely operated vehicle (ROV) with 80386-basedcomputers in the mother ship.andP;  The Jason Project performs ongoingresearch dives, often televising live images from Jason to schoolchildren or academic audiences over two-way satellite links.andO;Computers on Jason perform low-level monitoring, data collection,hardware control and communications 'multiplexing.' Data is sentvia two of three optical fibers connecting the ROV to the mothership.andP;  The topside computer controlling Jason runs the virtualreal-time executive multitasking operating system.andP;  Details of theLAN and computer systems are discussed.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     OceanographyCommunications EquipmentComputer SystemsSystem DesignSpecificationsWoods Hole Oceanographic Institution. Deep Submergence Laboratory.andO;Feature:   illustrationchartphotograph.andO;Caption:   Jason's two telemetry options. (chart)Jason remotely operated vehicle. (chart)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>